  "original_title": "Sri Lanka state radio station awards solar farm contract to private firm",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka state radio station awards solar farm contract to private firm",
      "author": "Mahadiya Hamza",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT\u00a0 \u2013 State-run Sri Lanka Broadcasting Corporation (SLBC) has awarded a contract to 3W Power Management Ltd to build a solar farm in Trincomalee,\u00a0 cabinet spokesman Minister Bandula Gunawardena said.",
        "Seven companies had responded to a tender to set up the solar farm at the premises of a short wave radio station in Kuchahaveli.",
        "\u201cState media corporations are being maintained with great difficulty,\u201d Minister Gunawardena said, speaking at the weekly cabinet press briefing on Tuesday August 23.",
        "\u201cThe reality is the tax income was given through the treasury to pay salaries and wages of these institutes and, given the current crisis, it can no longer be done.\u201d",
        "He said he has advised all state-owned media corporations to try and earn money to pay their salaries.",
        "\u201cThis is a similar project. By giving this land, SLBC will earn an income.\u201d",
        "As the country goes through its worst economic crisis since Independence, it is looking at ways to trim down its state expenditure, particularly in the form of wages.",
        "The Treasury can no longer sustain overstaffed state agencies with tax money so they need to get additional income from idle assets, analysts say.",
        "There are more than 1.5 million public sector employees in the country, which critics say are mostly political appointees who get massive benefits. (Colombo/Aug23/2022)"
      ],
